	<pb n="0001" facs="liv_001022_0001"/><!--pb/@n='1'-->
<lb/><p rend="right">57 Sloane <choice><abbr>St</abbr><expan>Street</expan></choice></p>
<lb/><p rend="right">18<hi rend="sup">th </hi>May</p>
<lb/><p rend="right">1857</p>
<lb/><p>My Dear Sir</p>
<lb/><p>I fear I shall 
<lb/>not have the pleasure 
<lb/>of meeting my old 
<lb/>teacher or any 
<lb/>of my <placeName>Glasgow</placeName>
<lb/> friends for a 
<lb/>few weeks. My 

	<pb n="0002" facs="liv_001022_0002"/><!--pb/@n='2'--> 
<lb/>Narrative does 
<lb/>not go on 
<lb/>so quickly as 
<lb/>I imagined it 
<lb/>might when it was 
<lb/>begun. <choice><orig>T</orig><reg>t</reg></choice>hat is 
<lb/>the only impediment 
<lb/>I have in the 
<lb/>way of visiting 
<lb/><placeName>Scotland</placeName>. As soon 
<lb/>as it is finished 

	<pb n="0003" facs="liv_001022_0003"/><!--pb/@n='3'--> 
<lb/>no time will be 
<lb/>lost and you 
<lb/>will in all probability 
<lb/>hear of my 
<lb/>being in <placeName>Glasgow</placeName><reg>.</reg></p>
<lb/><p>With kindest 
<lb/>salutations to 
<lb/>your Father &amp;c </p>
<lb/><p>I am &amp;c </p>
<lb/><p><persName>David Livingstone</persName></p>
<lb/><p>I fear my handwriting 
<lb/>does him no credit<reg>.</reg></p><!-- TODO SM: What is going on in this document - re: hands and newspaper clipping? Were these both added later. I have assumed that they were written/included with the letter after it was first written so I have commented it out. If you find the newspaper clipping REALLY interesting, we could create a new file to hold it -MH--><!-- Both added later, one a newspaper clipping and one handwritten in June 1857 --><!--TRANSC: Hand01 
<p rend="left"><placeName>Alexandria</placeName>F.C. School<lb/></p>
<p rend="left">8 June 1857 <lb/></p>
<p><persName>D<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi></hi>Livingstone</persName> was a Pupil of mine <lb/>at <placeName>Blantyre</placeName>Works for several years <lb/>subsequent to A. D. 1825, and if his <lb/>fist says little for his Teacher, he <lb/>is, at least, a credit to his country. <lb/></p>
<p rend="right"><persName>W<hi rend="superscript"><hi rend="underline">m</hi></hi>MacSkimming</persName><lb/></p>
--><!-- TRANSC: end Hand01 --><!-- TRANSC: Hand02 (newspaper cutting)
<p><persName>DR LIVINGSTONE'S</persName> SCHOOLMASTER.- <persName>Dr Livingstone</persName> <lb/>has, we understand, transmitted a copy of his Travels in <lb/><placeName>South Africa</placeName> to his old teacher, <persName>Mr M'Skimming, </persName>of <lb/>the Free Church School, <placeName>Alexandria,</placeName>with the following <lb/>inscription, written by himself - &quot;To <persName>William M<hi rend="superscript">c</hi>Skim <lb rend="hyphen"/>ming,</persName>with the kindest remembrances of his grateful <lb/>
pupil,<persName>David Livingstone.</persName><placeName>London,</placeName>20th Nov., 1857.&quot;<lb/>The Doctor obtained his education in early years <lb/>from Mr M'Skimming, when he was teacher in the village <lb/>school at Blantyre. At page 3 of his work he says, <lb/>in reference to his early days, &amp;Our schoolmaster - <lb/>happily still alive - was supported in part by the com <lb rend="hyphen"/>pany (Monteith &amp; Co.) He was attentive and kind, and <lb/>so moderate in his charges, that all who wished for edu <lb rend="hyphen"/>cation might have obtained it. <lb/>Many availed them <lb rend="hyphen"/>selves of the privilege; and some of my schoolfellows <lb/>now rank in positions far above what they appeared <lb/>ever like to come to when in the village schoool.&quot;-<lb/>Dumbarton Herald<lb/></p>
--><!-- TRANSC: end Hand02 -->
			
